'''Aducanumab''', sold under the brand name '''Aduhelm''', is an [[Anti-amyloid drugs|anti-amyloid drug]] designed to treat [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label">{{cite web | title=Aduhelm- aducanumab injection, solution | website=DailyMed | url=https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/drugInfo.cfm?setid=41706573-546f-6774-6872-5374726f6e67 | access-date=14 June 2021 | archive-date=14 June 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210614225021/https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/drugInfo.cfm?setid=41706573-546f-6774-6872-5374726f6e67 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="FDA PR 20210607" /> It is a [[monoclonal antibody]]<ref name="FDA PR 20210607" /><ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" /> that targets aggregated forms (plaque)<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Walsh S, Merrick R, Milne R, Brayne C | title = Aducanumab for Alzheimer's disease? | journal = BMJ | volume = 374 | article-number = n1682 | date = July 2021 | pmid = 34226181 | pmc = 8258645 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.n1682 }}</ref><ref name="sevigny phase 1">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sevigny J, Chiao P, Bussière T, Weinreb PH, Williams L, Maier M, Dunstan R, Salloway S, Chen T, Ling Y, O'Gorman J, Qian F, Arastu M, Li M, Chollate S, Brennan MS, Quintero-Monzon O, Scannevin RH, Arnold HM, Engber T, Rhodes K, Ferrero J, Hang Y, Mikulskis A, Grimm J, Hock C, Nitsch RM, Sandrock A | title = The antibody aducanumab reduces Aβ plaques in Alzheimer's disease | journal = Nature | volume = 537 | issue = 7618 | pages = 50–56 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27582220 | doi = 10.1038/nature19323 | s2cid = 205250312 | bibcode = 2016Natur.537...50S }}</ref> of [[amyloid beta]] (Aβ) found in the brains of people with Alzheimer's disease to reduce its buildup.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.14336/AD|title=Comparative Analysis of Aducanumab, Zagotenemab and Pioglitazone as Targeted Treatment Strategies for Alzheimer's Disease|journal=Aging and Disease|year=2021|vauthors=Abyadeh M, Gupta V, Gupta V, Chitranshi N, Wu Y, Amirkhani A, Meyfour A, Sheriff S, Shen T, Dhiman K, Salekdeh GH|volume=12|issue=8|pages=1964–1976 |pmid=34881080 |pmc=8612603}}</ref><ref name="lessons">{{cite journal | vauthors = Toyn J | title = What lessons can be learned from failed Alzheimer's disease trials? | journal = Expert Review of Clinical Pharmacology | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = 267–269 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25860157 | doi = 10.1586/17512433.2015.1034690 | s2cid = 35158630 | doi-access = free }}</ref> It was developed by [[Biogen]] and [[Eisai (company)|Eisai]].<ref name="full">{{Cite web | vauthors = Liu A |date=15 March 2022 |title=Biogen takes full control of troubled Aduhelm in revamped Eisai deal |url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/biogen-revamps-eisai-alzheimers-disease-pact-taking-full-control-over-troubled-aduhelm |access-date=21 March 2022 |website=Fierce Pharma |archive-date=21 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220321104126/https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/biogen-revamps-eisai-alzheimers-disease-pact-taking-full-control-over-troubled-aduhelm |url-status=live }}</ref> Aducanumab is given via [[intravenous infusion]].<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />

Aducanumab was approved for medical use in the United States by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) in June 2021,<ref name="Aduhelm Approval Package">{{cite web | title=Drug Approval Package: Aduhelm (aducanumab-avwa) | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=22 June 2021 | url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2021/761178Orig1s000TOC.cfm | access-date=1 September 2021 | archive-date=2 September 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902051939/https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2021/761178Orig1s000TOC.cfm }}</ref> in a controversial decision that led to the resignation of three advisers to the FDA in the absence of evidence that the medication is effective.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mahase E | title = Three FDA advisory panel members resign over approval of Alzheimer's drug | journal = BMJ | volume = 373 | article-number = n1503 | date = June 2021 | pmid = 34117086 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.n1503 | s2cid = 235405355 }}</ref><ref name="NPR resigned" /><ref name= BelluckThreeResign/> The FDA stated that it represents a first-of-its-kind treatment approved for Alzheimer's disease and that it is the first new treatment approved for Alzheimer's since 2003.<ref name="FDA PR 20210607">{{cite press release | title=FDA Grants Accelerated Approval for Alzheimer's Drug | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=7 June 2021 | url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-grants-accelerated-approval-alzheimers-drug | access-date=7 June 2021 | archive-date=8 June 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608011727/https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-grants-accelerated-approval-alzheimers-drug }} {{PD-notice}}</ref> Aducanumab's approval is controversial for numerous reasons including ambiguous clinical trial results regarding [[Efficacy#Medicine|efficacy]], the high cost of the medication and the very high rate of serious [[Adverse event|adverse events]].<ref name="WP 20210622">{{cite news | vauthors=McGinley L | title=FDA releases fresh details on internal debate over controversial Alzheimer's drug | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=22 June 2021 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/22/aducanumab-aduhelm-alzheimers-drug-controversy-/ | access-date=24 June 2021 | archive-date=19 November 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119195801/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/22/aducanumab-aduhelm-alzheimers-drug-controversy-/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= BelluckThreeResign/> The FDA considers it to be a [[first-in-class medication]].<ref name="New Drug Therapy Approvals 2021">{{cite report | title=Advancing Health Through Innovation: New Drug Therapy Approvals 2021 | website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) | date=13 May 2022 | url=https://www.fda.gov/media/155227/download | format=PDF | access-date=22 January 2023 | archive-date=6 December 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221206210020/https://www.fda.gov/media/155227/download | url-status=live }} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

In November 2020, a panel of outside experts for the FDA concluded that a pivotal study of aducanumab failed to show strong evidence that the medication worked, citing questionable efficacy and multiple red flags found with the data analysis.<ref name="controversy2" /> There were also significant health risks associated with the medication; brain swelling or brain bleeding was found in 41% of patients enrolled in the studies.<ref>{{Cite news |vauthors=Belluck P |date=22 November 2021 |title=Concerns Grow Over Safety of Aduhelm After Death of Patient Who Got the Drug |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/11/22/health/aduhelm-death-safety.html |access-date=20 July 2022 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=20 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720143252/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/11/22/health/aduhelm-death-safety.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Nevertheless, the medication was approved under the FDA's [[Accelerated approval (FDA)|accelerated approval pathway]], and the FDA requires Biogen to perform follow-up reviews to assure the medication is a safe and effective treatment for Alzheimer's disease.<ref name="FDA PR 20210607" /><ref name="FDA decision" /> The [[Office of Inspector General, US Department of Health and Human Services]] was asked to investigate interaction between the drug company and the FDA prior to the medication's approval.<ref name="CNN_Gumbrecht_20210709">{{cite news |vauthors=Gumbrecht J |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/07/09/health/aduhelm-fda-requests-inspection/index.html |title=Acting FDA commissioner calls for independent investigation into approval of Alzheimer's drug |work=CNN |date=9 July 2021 |access-date=1 September 2021 |archive-date=13 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813040816/https://www.cnn.com/2021/07/09/health/aduhelm-fda-requests-inspection/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Biogen abandoned the drug in January 2024, for financial reasons.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Biogen will stop selling its controversial Alzheimer's drug Aduhelm |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/biogen-plans-shut-controversial-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-106827709 |access-date=1 February 2024 |website=ABC News |language=en |archive-date=31 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131223738/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/biogen-plans-shut-controversial-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-106827709 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Medical uses ==
In the US, Aducanumab is [[Indication (medicine)|indicated]] for the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.<ref name="FDA PR 20210607" /><ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" /> In July 2021, the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) limited the indication to people with [[mild cognitive impairment]] or mild dementia stage of disease, the population in which treatment was initiated in clinical trials.<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />

== Mechanism of action ==
{{Main|Biochemistry of Alzheimer's disease#Amyloid hypothesis}}
Aducanumab is a monoclonal [[IgG1]] antibody that binds to the amyloid beta protein at amino acids 3–7, which is posited to result in slowing the progression of Alzheimer's disease.<ref name="sevigny phase 1"/> The mechanism is based on the [[amyloid hypothesis]], which posits that amyloid proteins cause Alzheimer's disease, hence removing amyloid should slow the progression of the disease.<ref name="lessons"/>

How the antibody accesses the plaques is under active research. One mechanism suggests the plaques are exposed to the lumen of blood vessels and the antibody accesses the plaques from the lumen side.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hansen SB, Wang H | title = The shared role of cholesterol in neuronal and peripheral inflammation | journal = Pharmacology & Therapeutics | volume = 249 | article-number = 108486 | date = September 2023 | pmid = 37390970 | doi = 10.1016/j.pharmthera.2023.108486 | s2cid = 259303593 | doi-access = free }}</ref> This assumes the plaque formed as a result of a leaky blood brain barrier and may also explain why there is hemorrhage after the plaques are removed.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hansen SB | title = Cholesterol's Function and Origin in the Alzheimer's Disease Brain | journal = Journal of Alzheimer's Disease | volume = 94 | issue = 2 | pages = 471–472 | date = 18 July 2023 | pmid = 37393509 | doi = 10.3233/JAD-230538 | s2cid = 259307724 }}</ref>

== Adverse effects ==
The most common serious adverse reactions reported are:<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* ARIA-E ([[Amyloid-related imaging abnormalities]]-[[Cerebral edema|edema [of the brain]]]) (35% of patients treated with Aduhelm vs 3% of patients treated with placebo) – Symptoms may include headache, changes in mental state, confusion, vomiting, nausea, tremor and gait disturbances.<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* "Headache" (21% vs 16%), including headache, head discomfort, migraine, [[migraine with aura]], and [[occipital neuralgia]].<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* ARIA-H [[intracerebral hemorrhage|microhemorrhages in the brain]] (19% vs 7%) – Symptoms can include headache, one-sided weakness, vomiting, seizures, decreased level of consciousness, and neck stiffness.<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* ARIA-H [[superficial siderosis]] ([[hemosiderin]]) (15% vs 2%)<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* Fall (15% vs 12%)<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* Diarrhea (9% vs 7%)<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />
* Confusion/delirium/altered mental status/disorientation (8% vs 4%)<ref name="Aduhelm FDA label" />

== History ==
Aducanumab was [[drug development|developed]] by [[Biogen|Biogen Inc.]], which licensed the medication candidate from [[Neurimmune]], who discovered it with the [[University of Zurich]].<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Zacks R | work = Xconomy | date = 20 November 2007 | url = http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/11/20/biogen-inks-380-million-deal-with-swiss-company/ | title = Biogen Inks $380 Million Deal with Swiss Company | access-date = 18 August 2015 | archive-date = 30 October 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191030072021/https://xconomy.com/boston/2007/11/20/biogen-inks-380-million-deal-with-swiss-company/ | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Approval for New Alzheimer's Drug Developed at UZH |url=https://www.media.uzh.ch/en/Press-Releases/2021/Approval.html |website=University of Zurich |date=7 June 2021 |access-date=16 November 2021 |archive-date=17 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117041052/https://www.media.uzh.ch/en/Press-Releases/2021/Approval.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Clinical trials===
Interim results from the second phase I study of the medication were reported in March 2015.<ref>{{Cite journal| vauthors = Sevigny J, Chiao P, Williams L, Chen T, Ling Y, O'Gorman J, Hock C, Nitsch RM, Sandrock A |date=July 2015|title=O4-04-05: Aducanumab (BIIB037), an anti-amyloid beta monoclonal antibody, in patients with prodromal or mild Alzheimer's disease: Interim results of a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, phase 1b study|journal=Alzheimer's & Dementia|volume=11|issue=7S_Part_6|page=277|doi=10.1016/j.jalz.2015.07.367|s2cid=54339030}}</ref>

A phase Ib study was published in August 2016, based on one year of "monthly intravenous infusions" of aducanumab, which brain scans to measure [[amyloid plaques]].<ref name="sevigny phase 1"/> Phase II trials were not required by the FDA and were not conducted by Biogen, a decision that received criticism from some experts.<ref name="STAT_Karlawish_20210530">{{cite news |vauthors=Karlawish J |title=If the FDA approves Biogen's Alzheimer's treatment, I won't prescribe it |url=https://www.statnews.com/2021/05/30/if-the-fda-approves-biogens-alzheimers-treatment-i-wont-prescribe-it/ |access-date=7 June 2021 |publisher=[[Stat (website)|STAT]] |date=30 May 2021 |archive-date=7 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607052152/https://www.statnews.com/2021/05/30/if-the-fda-approves-biogens-alzheimers-treatment-i-wont-prescribe-it/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= Belluck>{{cite news |vauthors=Belluck P, Robbins R |title=Alzheimer's Drug Poses a Dilemma for the F.D.A. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/health/alzheimers-aducanumab-fda.html |access-date=7 June 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 June 2021 |archive-date=19 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119195722/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/health/alzheimers-aducanumab-fda.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Phase III [[clinical trials]] were ongoing in September 2016,<ref name="sevigny phase 1"/> but were canceled in March 2019, after preliminary data from two [[Phases of clinical research|phase III]] trials suggested it would not meet the primary endpoint.<ref>{{cite magazine | vauthors = Ducharme J | date = 21 March 2019 | url = https://time.com/5555868/biogen-aducanumab-trials/ | title = Biogen Halts Promising Alzheimer's Drug Trials Due to Disappointing Results | magazine = Time | access-date = 21 March 2019 | archive-date = 2 June 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190602232841/http://time.com/5555868/biogen-aducanumab-trials/ | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Li Y | date = 21 March 2019 | title = Biogen posts its the worst day in 14 years after ending trial for blockbuster Alzheimer's drug | url = https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/21/biogen-shares-plunge-more-than-25percent-after-ending-trial-for-alzheimers-drug-aducanumab.html | work = CNBC | access-date = 21 March 2019 | archive-date = 7 June 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210607171231/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/21/biogen-shares-plunge-more-than-25percent-after-ending-trial-for-alzheimers-drug-aducanumab.html | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | vauthors = Annett T | work = Bloomberg News | title = Biogen Plunges More Than 25 Percent on Alzheimer's Setback | url = https://news.bloomberglaw.com/pharma-and-life-sciences/biogen-plunges-more-than-25-percent-on-alzheimers-setback-2-1 | access-date = 6 December 2019 | archive-date = 8 June 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210608082507/https://news.bloomberglaw.com/pharma-and-life-sciences/biogen-plunges-more-than-25-percent-on-alzheimers-setback-2-1 | url-status = live }}</ref> While imaging studies had shown that aducanumab did reduce amyloid plaque buildup, a [[surrogate endpoint]] for Alzheimer's treatment,<ref name="medscape mixed"/><ref name="surrogate amyloid">{{cite journal | vauthors = Manyara AM, Ciani O, Taylor RS | title = A call for better reporting of trials using surrogate primary endpoints | journal = Alzheimer's & Dementia | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | article-number = e12340 | date = January 2022 | pmid = 35910671 | doi = 10.1002/trc2.12340 | pmc = 9323346 | doi-access = free }}</ref> it had not meaningfully met its primary endpoints with regards to cognitive function and mental decline.<ref name="phase 3 cancel release">{{cite web |title=Biogen and Eisai to Discontinue Phase 3 ENGAGE and EMERGE Trials of aducanumab in Alzheimer's Disease |url=https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-and-eisai-discontinue-phase-3-engage-and-emerge-trials |website=[[Biogen]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231013002139/https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-and-eisai-discontinue-phase-3-engage-and-emerge-trials |archive-date=13 October 2023 |date=21 March 2019}}</ref>

On 22 October 2019, Biogen announced that it would be restarting the FDA approval process for aducanumab stating that analysis of a larger dataset from its Phase 3 trials<ref>{{cite news|vauthors=Roberts M|date=22 October 2019|title=First drug to slow Alzheimer's may be available soon|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-50137041|access-date=22 October 2019|archive-date=5 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205125806/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-50137041|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|vauthors=Foster L|date=26 October 2019|title=Drug 'could be biggest Alzheimer's development'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/science-environment-50186508/dementia-new-alzheimer-s-drug-could-slow-rate-at-which-disease-progresses|access-date=26 October 2019|website=BBC News|archive-date=19 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219064956/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/science-environment-50186508/dementia-new-alzheimer-s-drug-could-slow-rate-at-which-disease-progresses|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|vauthors=Kunkle F|date=6 December 2019|title=Biogen's potential new drug for Alzheimer's disease gets cautiously optimistic review following presentation|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2019/12/05/biogens-potential-new-drug-alzheimers-disease-gets-cautiously-optimistic-review-following-presentation/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=6 December 2019|archive-date=2 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102034406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2019/12/05/biogens-potential-new-drug-alzheimers-disease-gets-cautiously-optimistic-review-following-presentation/|url-status=live}}</ref> showed that the drug reduced clinical decline in patients with early Alzheimer's disease when given at higher doses.<ref>{{cite web|vauthors=Howard J, Gumbrecht J|date=23 October 2019|title=Drugmaker to seek approval for Alzheimer's treatment|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/22/health/biogen-alzheimers-drug-fda/index.html|access-date=23 October 2019|work=CNN|archive-date=24 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210824155106/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/22/health/biogen-alzheimers-drug-fda/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In one trial, "EMERGE",(NCT02484547), an analysis split by dose indicated that high doses reduced rate of decline by 22% versus placebo. However, an identical trial, "ENGAGE", failed to replicate this, with a non-significant 2% reduction in decline compared to placebo. Researchers had theorized that the difference may have stemmed from a change in protocol which affected more of the participants of the later study EMERGE than the earlier ENGAGE study's participants.<ref name="medscape mixed">{{cite web |vauthors=McNamara D |date=28 May 2020 |title=Mixed Results for Aducanumab in Two Phase 3 AD Trials |url=https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/931294 |website=Medscape |access-date=11 August 2020 |archive-date=8 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608082509/https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/931294 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="STAT_20191022">{{Cite web | vauthors = Herper M |date=22 October 2019 |title=In shocking reversal, Biogen to submit Alzheimer's drug for approval |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/in-shocking-reversal-biogen-to-submit-experimental-alzheimers-drug-for-approval/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405213257/https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/in-shocking-reversal-biogen-to-submit-experimental-alzheimers-drug-for-approval/ |archive-date=5 April 2023 |access-date=15 November 2023 |website=[[Scientific American]] |quote="In one study, called Emerge, patients on the high-dose aducanumab had a 23% reduction in their rate of decline compared to those on placebo; those who were on the low dose were 11% lower than placebo, but that result was not statistically significant. But in the second trial, Engage, the decrease was only 2% in patients on the high dose."}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=22 October 2019|title=Biogen Plans Regulatory Filing for Aducanumab in Alzheimer's Disease Based on New Analysis of Larger Dataset from Phase 3 Studies|url=http://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-plans-regulatory-filing-aducanumab-alzheimers-disease|access-date=22 October 2019|publisher=Biogen|archive-date=29 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200529043354/https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-plans-regulatory-filing-aducanumab-alzheimers-disease|url-status=live}}</ref> The FDA accepted Biogen's aducanumab [[Biologics License Application]] (BLA) on 7 August 2020 with a Priority Review.<ref>{{Cite web| title = FDA Accepts BLA for Biogen's Alzheimer's Drug, Grants Priority Review| work = BioSpace| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 7 August 2020| url = https://www.biospace.com/article/biogen-jumps-after-fda-accepts-bla-for-alzheimer-s-drug-aducanumab-grants-priority-review/| archive-date = 2 September 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210902000224/https://www.biospace.com/article/biogen-jumps-after-fda-accepts-bla-for-alzheimer-s-drug-aducanumab-grants-priority-review/| url-status = live}}</ref>

===FDA review and approval===
In November 2020, a panel of outside experts on the FDA's Peripheral and Central Nervous System Advisory Committee concluded that a pivotal study of aducanumab failed to show "strong evidence" that the medication worked, along with potential safety issues, and suggested that the FDA not approve aducanumab, citing questionable efficacy and multiple "red flags" found with the data analysis.<ref name="controversy2">{{cite news|vauthors=Marchione M, Perrone M|date=6 November 2020|title=FDA panel urges rejection of experimental Alzheimer's drug|url=https://apnews.com/article/dementia-alzheimers-disease-8ce05b6c22ca4e649d299bb3abafe43a|work=Associated Press|access-date=8 June 2021|archive-date=17 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117003417/https://apnews.com/article/dementia-alzheimers-disease-8ce05b6c22ca4e649d299bb3abafe43a|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="WP 20210622" />

Aducanumab was approved for medical use in the United States in June 2021,<ref name="FDA PR 20210607" /><ref name="Aduhelm Approval Package" /><ref name="FDA decision">{{cite web|date=7 June 2021|title=FDA's Decision to Approve New Treatment for Alzheimer's Disease|url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/news-events-human-drugs/fdas-decision-approve-new-treatment-alzheimers-disease|access-date=7 June 2021|publisher=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA)|archive-date=8 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608011927/https://www.fda.gov/drugs/news-events-human-drugs/fdas-decision-approve-new-treatment-alzheimers-disease}}</ref> and was the first Alzheimer's treatment to receive approval through an accelerated pathway.<ref>{{Cite news | vauthors = Bell J |date=6 February 2023 |title=Eisai gives first glimpse into Alzheimer's drug launch |work=BiopharmaDive |publisher=[[Informa]] |location=Washington, D.C. |url=https://www.biopharmadive.com/news/eisai-alzheimers-leqembi-launch-earnings/642067/ |access-date=11 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206223238/https://www.biopharmadive.com/news/eisai-alzheimers-leqembi-launch-earnings/642067/ |archive-date=6 February 2023}}</ref>

===Coverage in the United States===
The Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) finalized a coverage decision for aducanumab in April 2022. Coverage for aducanumab will be limited to individuals participating in randomized controlled trials to confirm the efficacy and safety for the Medicare population.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NCA - Monoclonal Antibodies Directed Against Amyloid for the Treatment of Alzheimer's Disease (CAG-00460N) - Decision Memo |url=https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/view/ncacal-decision-memo.aspx?proposed=N&ncaid=305 |access-date=9 June 2022 |website=[[Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services]] |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605000000/https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/view/ncacal-decision-memo.aspx?proposed=N&ncaid=305 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Medicare Officially Limits Coverage of Aduhelm to Patients in Clinical Trials | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=7 April 2022 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/07/health/aduhelm-medicare-alzheimers.html | access-date=9 July 2023 | archive-date=23 March 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230323205646/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/07/health/aduhelm-medicare-alzheimers.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

===European review===
Aducanumab was rejected for medical use in the European Union in December 2021, by the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA).<ref>{{Cite web |date= February 2022 |title=Refusal of the marketing authorisation for Aduhelm (aducanumab) EMA/112932/2022 Rev.1 / EMEA/H/C/005558 |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/medicine-qa/questions-answers-refusal-marketing-authorisation-aduhelm-aducanumab_en.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217112812/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/summaries-opinion/aduhelm |archive-date=17 December 2021 |website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Aducanumab rejected in the EU: Biogen to ask EMA to re-examine application|url=https://www.biopharma-reporter.com/Article/2021/12/20/Aducanumab-rejected-in-the-EU-Biogen-will-ask-EMA-to-re-examine-application|access-date=21 December 2021|website=biopharma reporter|date=20 December 2021 |archive-date=20 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220123630/https://www.biopharma-reporter.com/Article/2021/12/20/Aducanumab-rejected-in-the-EU-Biogen-will-ask-EMA-to-re-examine-application|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=17 December 2021|title=Alzheimer's drug aducanumab not approved for use in EU|work=[[BBC News Online]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-59699907|access-date=21 December 2021|archive-date=21 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211221005217/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-59699907|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2022, Biogen withdrew its application for a marketing authorization of aducanumab (Aduhelm) for the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.<ref>{{cite web | title=Aduhelm: Withdrawn application | website=[[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) | date=9 March 2023 | url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/withdrawn-applications/aduhelm | access-date=9 July 2023 | archive-date=10 July 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230710034259/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/withdrawn-applications/aduhelm | url-status=live }}</ref>

===Abandonment===
In March 2022, Eisai relinquished full control over marketing decisions to Biogen, retaining only rights to partial royalties.<ref name="full" />

In January 2024, Biogen announced that for financial reasons, it was terminating the post-marketing clinical study (called "ENVISION"), abandoning commercial development of Aduhelm, terminating its lease of patent rights from [[Neurimmune]], and redirecting resources to its other Alzheimer's treatments.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-realign-resources-alzheimers-disease-franchise |title=Biogen to Realign Resources for Alzheimer's Disease Franchise |date=31 January 2024 |access-date=31 January 2024 |archive-date=31 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131223739/https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-realign-resources-alzheimers-disease-franchise |url-status=live }}</ref> Availability is expected to continue for existing commercial patients until November 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/biogen-plans-shut-controversial-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-106827709 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Biogen will stop selling its controversial Alzheimer's drug Aduhelm |first=Tom |last=Murphy |date=31 January 2024 |access-date=31 January 2024 |archive-date=31 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131223738/https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/biogen-plans-shut-controversial-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-106827709 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Society and culture ==
=== Efficacy ===

The June 2021 approval of the medication by the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) was controversial because clinical trials gave conflicting results on its effectiveness.<ref name="WP 20210622" /><ref name="controversy2"/><ref name="Medscape_20210505"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-57383763 |title=US approves first new Alzheimer's drug in 20 years |website=BBC News Online |date=7 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |archive-date=30 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210930032021/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-57383763 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NYT 20210607">{{cite news |vauthors=Belluck P, Robbins R |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/07/health/aduhelm-fda-alzheimers-drug.html |title=F.D.A. Approves Alzheimer's Drug Despite Fierce Debate Over Whether It Works |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=7 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |archive-date=14 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211114103444/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/07/health/aduhelm-fda-alzheimers-drug.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Specific criticisms of the approval included: insufficient evidence of efficacy, that the drug offers false hope, and that the high cost will adversely impact patient finances and Medicare budget.<ref>{{cite news | vauthors=McGinley L | title=Furor rages over FDA approval of controversial Alzheimer's drug | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=17 June 2021 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/17/alzheimers-drug-controversy/ | access-date=19 June 2021 | archive-date=19 November 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119195736/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/17/alzheimers-drug-controversy/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="WP 20210622" />

Ten of the eleven outside experts that had served on the FDA's Peripheral and Central Nervous System Advisory Committee voted in November 2020 against approving aducanumab.<ref name="NPR resigned" /><ref name= BelluckThreeResign>{{Cite news|vauthors=Belluck P, Robbins R|date=10 June 2021|title=Three F.D.A. Advisers Resign Over Agency's Approval of Alzheimer's Drug|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/10/health/aduhelm-fda-resign-alzheimers.html|access-date=14 June 2021|archive-date=14 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211114103425/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/10/health/aduhelm-fda-resign-alzheimers.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Medscape_20210505">{{cite web| vauthors= Ault A| date= 5 May 2021| title= FDA Reviewers: Why We Are Against Approval of Aducanumab for Alzheimer's| url= https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/950565?src=ppc_google_rlsa-traf_mscp_news-perspectives-hdle-cohort_md_us| work= Medscape Medical News| access-date= 9 June 2021| archive-date= 10 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210610051307/https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/950565?src=ppc_google_rlsa-traf_mscp_news-perspectives-hdle-cohort_md_us| url-status= live}}</ref><ref name="STAT_20210610">{{Cite web| title = Third member of FDA expert committee resigns over Alzheimer's decision| work = STAT| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 10 June 2021| url = https://www.statnews.com/2021/06/10/third-member-of-fda-expert-committee-resigns-over-controversial-alzheimers-therapy-decision/| archive-date = 2 September 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210902032242/https://www.statnews.com/2021/06/10/third-member-of-fda-expert-committee-resigns-over-controversial-alzheimers-therapy-decision/| url-status = live}}</ref> Soon after the approval was announced in early June 2021, three of the panelists who had voted against aducanumab's approval resigned in protest.<ref name="NPR resigned" /><ref name="Medscape_20210505"/><ref name="STAT_20210610"/><ref>{{cite news | vauthors= McGinley L | date= 9 June 2021 | title= Two members of an FDA advisory committee quit after approval of controversial Alzheimer's drug | url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/09/alzheimers-drug-controversy/ | newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] | access-date= 9 June 2021 | archive-date= 10 June 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210610145317/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/06/09/alzheimers-drug-controversy/ | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|vauthors=Langreth R|date=10 June 2021|title=Harvard Expert Quits FDA Panel as Furor Over Biogen Drug Grows|work=Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-10/harvard-expert-quits-fda-panel-as-furor-over-biogen-drug-grows|access-date=10 June 2021|archive-date=10 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610213621/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-10/harvard-expert-quits-fda-panel-as-furor-over-biogen-drug-grows|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the resigning panelists said that the FDA move was "probably the worst drug approval decision in recent US history".<ref name="NPR resigned"/><ref name="Bloomberg">{{Cite news| title = Harvard Expert Quits FDA Panel as Biogen Drug Furor Grows| work = Bloomberg| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 10 June 2021| url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-10/harvard-expert-quits-fda-panel-as-furor-over-biogen-drug-grows| archive-date = 10 June 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210610213621/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-10/harvard-expert-quits-fda-panel-as-furor-over-biogen-drug-grows| url-status = live}}</ref>

===Process concerns===

[[Public Citizen]]<ref>{{cite web | date=7 June 2021 | title=Statement: FDA's Decision to Approve Aducanumab for Alzheimer's Disease Shows Reckless Disregard for Science, Severely Damages Agency's Credibility | url=https://www.citizen.org/news/statement-fdas-decision-to-approve-aducanumab-for-alzheimers-disease-shows-reckless-disregard-for-science-severely-damages-agencys-credibility/ | website=Public Citizen | access-date=11 June 2021 | archive-date=11 June 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210611195654/https://www.citizen.org/news/statement-fdas-decision-to-approve-aducanumab-for-alzheimers-disease-shows-reckless-disregard-for-science-severely-damages-agencys-credibility/ | url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Institute for Clinical and Economic Review]] criticized the approval.<ref>{{Cite web|title=ICER Issues Statement on the FDA's Approval of Aducanumab for Alzheimer's Disease|url=https://icer.org/news-insights/press-releases/icer-issues-statement-on-the-fdas-approval-of-aducanumab-for-alzheimers-disease/|access-date=11 June 2021|website=ICER|archive-date=11 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210611023330/https://icer.org/news-insights/press-releases/icer-issues-statement-on-the-fdas-approval-of-aducanumab-for-alzheimers-disease/|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Joe Manchin|Senator Joe Manchin]] heavily criticized the decision and said that the acting director of the FDA, [[Janet Woodcock]], "should be quickly replaced."<ref>{{Cite news|vauthors=Edney A|date=17 June 2021|title=Key Democrat Manchin Bashes FDA Leader on Alzheimer's Approval|work=Bloomberg News|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-17/key-democrat-manchin-bashes-fda-leader-on-alzheimer-s-approval|access-date=20 June 2021|archive-date=2 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210702204557/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-06-17/key-democrat-manchin-bashes-fda-leader-on-alzheimer-s-approval|url-status=live}}</ref> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the review process for the medication "took several unusual turns, including a decision for the FDA to work far more closely with Biogen than is typical in a regulatory review."<ref>{{Cite news| title = How Aduhelm, an Unproven Alzheimer's Drug, Got Approved| work = New York Times| date = 20 July 2021| access-date = 5 August 2021| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/19/health/alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-fda.html| vauthors = Belluck P, Kaplan S, Robbins R| archive-date = 4 August 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210804193930/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/19/health/alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-fda.html| url-status = live}}</ref> According to a 2022 report released by two House committees,<ref name="joint report">{{Cite web |date=December 2022 |title=The High Price of Aduhelm's Approval: An Investigation into FDA's Atypical Review Process and Biogen's Aggressive Launch Plans |url=https://energycommerce.house.gov/sites/democrats.energycommerce.house.gov/files/documents/Final%20Aduhelm%20Report_12.29.22.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221231030409/https://energycommerce.house.gov/sites/democrats.energycommerce.house.gov/files/documents/Final%20Aduhelm%20Report_12.29.22.pdf |archive-date=31 December 2022 |access-date=31 December 2022 |publisher=[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]/[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Accountability|Committee on Oversight and Accountability]]}}</ref> [[FDA]] and Biogen worked in concert to receive accelerated approval at a cost to patients of $56,000 a year.<ref>{{Cite news | vauthors = Johnson M |date=29 December 2022 |title=House investigation faults FDA, Biogen for Alzheimer's drug approval |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2022/12/29/alzheimers-fda-biogen-aduhelm/ |url-status=live |access-date=31 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230101227/https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2022/12/29/alzheimers-fda-biogen-aduhelm/ |archive-date=30 December 2022}}</ref>

FDA officials met with "Biogen executives" using "back channels" in the months prior to Aducanumab's FDA approval.<ref name="Forbes_Rosenbaum_20210709"/><ref name="statnews_20210629">{{Cite web| title = How Biogen used an FDA back channel to win Alzheimer's drug approval| work = [[Stat (website)|STAT]]| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 29 June 2021| url = https://www.statnews.com/2021/06/29/biogen-fda-alzheimers-drug-approval-aduhelm-project-onyx/| vauthors = Feuerstein A, Herper M, Garde D| archive-date = 2 September 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210902011030/https://www.statnews.com/2021/06/29/biogen-fda-alzheimers-drug-approval-aduhelm-project-onyx/| url-status = live}}</ref>

In July 2021, the FDA's acting commissioner, Janet Woodcock, requested that the [[Office of Inspector General, US Department of Health and Human Services]] conduct an independent review of interactions between FDA officials and Biogen representatives prior to the FDA's approval of aducanumab.<ref name="CNN_Gumbrecht_20210709"/><ref name="Forbes_Rosenbaum_20210709">{{Cite web| vauthors = Rosenbaum L| title = FDA Commissioner Calls For Inspector General Probe Into Biogen Alzheimer's Drug Approval| work = [[Forbes]]| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 9 July 2021| url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2021/07/09/fda-commissioner-calls-for-inspector-general-probe-into-biogen-alzheimers-drug-approval/| archive-date = 19 November 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211119195723/https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2021/07/09/fda-commissioner-calls-for-inspector-general-probe-into-biogen-alzheimers-drug-approval/| url-status = live}}</ref> It was reported that the OIG will also investigate the "accelerated approval pathway, the regulatory mechanism" the FDA used to approve Aducanumab in spite of "conflicting data over whether it could actually slow Alzheimer's patients' mental decline."<ref name="endpts_Mast_20210804">{{Cite web| title = HHS extends Aduhelm investigation into the accelerated approval pathway, wading into a brewing controversy| work = Endpoints News| vauthors = Jason M| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 4 August 2021| url = https://endpts.com/hhs-extends-aduhelm-investigation-into-the-accelerated-approval-pathway-wading-into-a-brewing-controversy/| archive-date = 2 September 2021| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210902003138/https://endpts.com/hhs-extends-aduhelm-investigation-into-the-accelerated-approval-pathway-wading-into-a-brewing-controversy/| url-status = live}}</ref>

Patient advocacy groups had lobbied heavily for the approval of the medication for a debilitating condition with very few therapy choices.<ref name="NYT 20210607" /> Advocacy groups such as [[Alzheimer's Association]],<ref>{{cite web | title= It's a New Day in the Fight Against Alzheimer's — Aducanumab Approved | url= https://www.alz.org/get-involved-now/new-day | website= [[Alzheimer's Association]] | access-date= 11 June 2021 | archive-date= 10 June 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210610164349/https://www.alz.org/get-involved-now/new-day }}</ref> [[Alzheimer Society of Canada]],<ref>{{cite web | title= First new treatment for Alzheimer's disease approved in nearly two decades offers hope for people living with dementia | date= 7 June 2021 | url= https://alzheimer.ca/en/whats-happening/news/first-new-treatment-alzheimers-disease-approved-nearly-two-decades-offers-hope | website= Alzheimer Society of Canada | access-date= 11 June 2021 | archive-date= 10 June 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210610034102/https://alzheimer.ca/en/whats-happening/news/first-new-treatment-alzheimers-disease-approved-nearly-two-decades-offers-hope | url-status= live }}</ref> and [[Alzheimer's Foundation of America]]<ref>{{cite web | title= Alzheimer's Foundation of America Statement on FDA Approving First New Alzheimer's Medication in Nearly 20 Years | url= https://alzfdn.org/alzheimers-foundation-of-america-statement-on-fda-approving-first-new-alzheimers-medication-in-nearly-20-years/ | website= Alzheimer's Foundation of America | date= 7 June 2021 | access-date= 11 June 2021 | archive-date= 11 June 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210611202922/https://alzfdn.org/alzheimers-foundation-of-america-statement-on-fda-approving-first-new-alzheimers-medication-in-nearly-20-years/ | url-status= live }}</ref> were also in favor of the decision. Alzheimer's Association denies their support for aducanumab was influenced by the at least $1.4 million they received since 2018 from [[Biogen]] and [[Eisai (company)|Eisai]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Alzheimer's Association Denies Conflict in Aducanumab Support |url=https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/947047 |access-date=8 August 2022 |website=Medscape |archive-date=8 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220808184820/https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/947047 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2022, a congressional investigation by the House Committee on Oversight and Reform and the House Committee on Energy and Commerce was released that found the FDA had broken its own protocols in reviewing and approving aducanumab.<ref name="thehill.com" /> The investigation found that the FDA had held unreported meetings and failed to gain internal consensus before engaging in collaboration with the drugmaker.<ref name="thehill.com" /> The FDA also gave the medication a broad label, allowing it to be used on all Alzheimer's patients regardless of severity, even though it had only been tested on people with early Alzheimer's and mild symptoms.<ref name="thehill.com" /> The report also questioned the agency's decision to abruptly switch from the traditional approval pathway to the accelerated approval pathway to grant approval in the medication's label to a broad patient population.<ref name="thehill.com">{{Cite web | vauthors = Weixel N |date=29 December 2022 |title=House investigation faults FDA approval of Alzheimer's drug Aduhelm as 'rife with irregularities' |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/3792154-house-investigation-faults-fda-approval-of-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-as-rife-with-irregularities/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230104154920/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/3792154-house-investigation-faults-fda-approval-of-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-as-rife-with-irregularities/ |archive-date=4 January 2023 |access-date=4 January 2023 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>

The investigation further reported concerns related to Biogen's "aggressive launch and marketing plans." They obtained documents that show the company estimated a peak revenue of $18 billion per year with an initial price of $56,000 for patient treatment per year, despite what the Committees described as "a lack of demonstrated clinical benefit in a broad population." Documents show that Biogen estimated aducanumab would cost the Medicare program $12 billion a year and that Medicare patients would incur out-of-pocket costs that could account for as much as 20% of their income.<ref name="joint report"/> Aware that the high price would trigger "pushback" from payers and providers, "Biogen developed an external narrative about the drug's value to sell to the patients and the public." According to the report, Biogen knew its $56,000 launch price was "unjustifiably high," but company executives wanted to "make history" and "establish Aduhelm as one of the top pharmaceutical launches of all time." Findings showed that Biogen estimated that from 2020 to 2024, it would spend more than $3.3 billion on sales and marketing,<ref name="thehill.com" /> more than twice the development costs of the drug.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/29/health/biogen-aduhelm-alzheimers-drug-investigation/index.html |title=House investigation says FDA approval process of Alzheimer's drug was 'rife with irregularities' |author=Jen Christensen |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=29 December 2022 |access-date=31 January 2024 |archive-date=31 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131224050/https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/29/health/biogen-aduhelm-alzheimers-drug-investigation/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Economics and cost ===
{{see also|Lecanemab#Economics}}<!--closely related, with overlapping factors and analysis-->
Treatment using aducanumab is estimated to cost {{US$|56,000}} per year, and Biogen's CEO stated that they would maintain this price for at least four years.<ref name="WaPo_Cunningham_20210616">{{cite news |title=The Health 202: The pricey new Alzheimer's drug adds to the pressure for drug price controls |vauthors=Cunningham PW |date=16 June 2021 |access-date=1 September 2021 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/16/health-202-pricey-new-alzheimer-drug-adds-pressure-drug-price-controls/ |archive-date=19 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119195737/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/16/health-202-pricey-new-alzheimer-drug-adds-pressure-drug-price-controls/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://seekingalpha.com/news/3703844-biogen-ceo-committed-to-gathering-new-data-on-fda-approved-alzheimers-drug |title=Biogen CEO: committed to gathering new data on FDA-approved Alzheimer's drug |date=7 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |archive-date=7 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607192310/https://seekingalpha.com/news/3703844-biogen-ceo-committed-to-gathering-new-data-on-fda-approved-alzheimers-drug |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Kaiser Family Foundation]] (KFF) researchers said that a conservative estimate of the cost to Medicare would be $29 billion in one year. This is based on 500,000 Medicare patients potentially receiving Aduhelm. To put this in perspective—in 2019, "total Medicare spending for all doctor-administered drugs reached $37 billion."<ref name="KFF_20210901">{{Cite web | title = FDA's Approval of Biogen's New Alzheimer's Drug Has Huge Cost Implications for Medicare and Beneficiaries| work = [[Kaiser Family Foundation]] (KFF)| access-date = 1 September 2021| date = 10 June 2021| url = https://www.kff.org/medicare/issue-brief/fdas-approval-of-biogens-new-alzheimers-drug-has-huge-cost-implications-for-medicare-and-beneficiaries/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210901230425/https://www.kff.org/medicare/issue-brief/fdas-approval-of-biogens-new-alzheimers-drug-has-huge-cost-implications-for-medicare-and-beneficiaries/ |archive-date=1 September 2021}}</ref><ref name="economist_20210715"/> For patients with applicable health insurance and/or Medicare, the drug is a tier 5 specialty drug.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How do drug tiers work? |url=https://www.bcbsm.com/medicare/help/understanding-plans/pharmacy-prescription-drugs/tiers.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210615043225/https://www.bcbsm.com/medicare/help/understanding-plans/pharmacy-prescription-drugs/tiers.html |archive-date=15 June 2021 |access-date=14 June 2021 |website=[[Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=What Medicare Part D drug plans cover |url=https://www.medicare.gov/drug-coverage-part-d/what-medicare-part-d-drug-plans-cover |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119101159/https://www.medicare.gov/drug-coverage-part-d/what-medicare-part-d-drug-plans-cover |archive-date=19 November 2021 |access-date=14 June 2021 |website=US [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]]}}</ref> and the [[copayment]] for such therapy would be about $11,500 annually.<ref>{{cite web | title= Medicare Copays For New Alzheimer's Drug Could Reach $11,500 Annually | date= 10 June 2021 | url= https://www.npr.org/2021/06/10/1005319693/medicare-copays-for-new-alzheimers-drug-could-reach-11-500-annually | agency= Associated Press | website= [[NPR]] | access-date= 11 June 2021 | archive-date= 10 June 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210610233648/https://www.npr.org/2021/06/10/1005319693/medicare-copays-for-new-alzheimers-drug-could-reach-11-500-annually | url-status= live }}</ref><ref name="NPR resigned">{{cite news | title=3 Experts Have Resigned From An FDA Committee Over Alzheimer's Drug Approval | website=NPR | date=11 June 2021 | url=https://www.npr.org/2021/06/11/1005567149/3-experts-have-resigned-from-an-fda-committee-over-alzheimers-drug-approval | access-date=11 June 2021 | archive-date=11 June 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210611183728/https://www.npr.org/2021/06/11/1005567149/3-experts-have-resigned-from-an-fda-committee-over-alzheimers-drug-approval | url-status=live }}</ref> An initial [[brain positron emission tomography]] (PET scan) is required to detect the presence of amyloid beta; since 2013, it has not been covered by Medicare,<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 September 2013 |title=National Coverage Analysis (NCA) Beta Amyloid Positron Emission Tomography in Dementia and Neurodegenerative Disease (CAG-00431N) |url=https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/view/ncacal-decision-memo.aspx?proposed=N&NCAId=265&NCDId=211&ncdver=5&IsPopup=y&bc=AAAAAAAACAAAAAAA& |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210628103048/https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/details/nca-decision-memo.aspx?NCAId=265&NCDId=211&ncdver=5&IsPopup=y&bc=AAAAAAAACAAAAAAA& |archive-date=28 June 2021 |access-date=28 June 2021 |website=[[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]] (CMS)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | vauthors = Foley KE, Lim D, Roubein R |date=15 June 2021 |title=New Alzheimer's drug could be 'devastating' for Medicare |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/06/15/fda-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-costs-494546?cid=apn |access-date=19 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210627195604/https://www.politico.com/news/2021/06/15/fda-alzheimers-drug-aduhelm-costs-494546?cid=apn |archive-date=27 June 2021}}</ref> and as of 2018, can cost $2,250 – $10,700.<ref>{{cite web | last=Poslusny | first=Catherine | title=How much should your PET scan cost? | website=New Choice Health Blog | date=31 July 2018 | url=https://www.newchoicehealth.com/pet-scan/cost | access-date=19 June 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624202107/https://www.newchoicehealth.com/pet-scan/cost |archive-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> In November 2021, the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS), announced a 14% increase in Medicare Part B premiums for 2022 in response to the expected cost of Aduhelm.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 January 2022 |title=Medicare's Coverage Decision for the New Alzheimer's Drug and Why It Matters |url=https://www.kff.org/policy-watch/medicares-coverage-decision-for-the-new-alzheimers-drug-and-why-it-matters/ |access-date=20 July 2022 |website=KFF |archive-date=20 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720143255/https://www.kff.org/policy-watch/medicares-coverage-decision-for-the-new-alzheimers-drug-and-why-it-matters/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The annual price of Aduhelm and the controversial 2021 FDA approval process resulted in the launch of an investigation by the United States House of Representatives, the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|Committee on Oversight and Reform]], and the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]], making Aduhelm the "poster-child" for the [[Elijah Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act]] (H.R.3) campaign.<ref name="economist_20210715">{{Cite news| issn = 0013-0613| title = Aduhelm may not cure Alzheimer's, but it might help fix drug prices| newspaper = The Economist| access-date = 20 July 2021| date = 15 July 2021| url = https://www.economist.com/united-states/2021/07/15/aduhelm-may-not-cure-alzheimers-but-it-might-help-fix-drug-prices |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210901222851/https://www.economist.com/united-states/2021/07/15/aduhelm-may-not-cure-alzheimers-but-it-might-help-fix-drug-prices |archive-date=1 September 2021}}</ref><ref name="WaPo_Cunningham_20210616"/> By December 2021, Biogen announced a 50% price cut for Aduhelm, from $56,000 to $28,200; this would have no impact on the cost of brain scans.<ref>{{Cite news |vauthors=Khandekar A |date=20 December 2021 |title=Biogen halves price of Alzheimer's drug to $28,200 |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/biogen-cut-price-alzheimers-drug-by-half-2021-12-20/ |access-date=20 July 2022 |archive-date=20 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220123628/https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/biogen-cut-price-alzheimers-drug-by-half-2021-12-20/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Sales ===
Sales of the medication are far lower than analyst's predictions.<ref name="STAT 20210922" /> As of September 2021, only about 100 people had received the drug,<ref name="STAT 20210922">{{cite news | url = https://www.statnews.com/2021/09/22/biogens-aduhelm-sales-slower-than-disclosed-forcing-company-to-consider-cost-cutting-measures | title = Biogen's Aduhelm sales slower than disclosed, forcing company to consider cost-cutting measures | vauthors = Feuerstein A, Garde D | date = 22 September 2021 | publisher = [[Stat (website)|Stat]] | access-date = 11 December 2021 | archive-date = 17 December 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211217131446/https://www.statnews.com/2021/09/22/biogens-aduhelm-sales-slower-than-disclosed-forcing-company-to-consider-cost-cutting-measures/ | url-status = live }}</ref> far short of the 10,000 that would be needed by the end of 2021 to meet Wall Street expectations for Biogen's revenue.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/biogen-s-pipeline-prospects-may-not-be-enough-to-shield-from-sluggish-aduhelm-uptake | title = Struggling with Alzheimer's launch, Biogen couldn't present 'clear case for growth' outside of Aduhelm | vauthors = Higgins-Dunn N | date = 22 September 2021 | publisher = Fierce Pharma | access-date = 11 December 2021 | archive-date = 11 December 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211211212801/https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/biogen-s-pipeline-prospects-may-not-be-enough-to-shield-from-sluggish-aduhelm-uptake | url-status = live }}</ref>

